{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487151","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487151"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:59:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:59:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"265"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"265","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/265"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.11,0.04,0.13,0.61]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"265"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51975"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"265","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/265"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"265"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37278"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"316"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"1227"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"3915"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4847"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6196"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14537"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42044"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42991"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44749"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51975","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51975"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a four-day history of constipation, abdominal pain and urinary frequency. He says he has been voiding about eight times each day, passing more urine than usual. His wife reports that he shows moderate confusion, and this is consistent throughout the day. Two months ago he was diagnosed with stage II squamous cell carcinoma of the lung and is currently undergoing a course of chemotherapy. His regular medications include paracetamol and metoclopramide.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His vital signs are within normal limits. Abdominal examination reveals mild generalised tenderness without guarding or rebound. The remainder of the physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for his current problems?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Medication side effect","Urinary tract infection","Brain metastases","Diabetes insipidus","Paraneoplastic syndrome"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EHypercalcaemia should be considered in patients that present with abdominal pain, constipation and polyuria. Abdominal pain may be caused by constipation, which has many causes of its own, however, in combination with polyuria and confusion, the diagnosis of hypercalcaemia should be considered. Hypercalcaemia is most commonly caused by increased parathyroid hormone (primary or tertiary hyperparathyroidism, secondary hyperparathyroidism is caused by hypocalcaemia). The second most common cause is malignancy. Lastly, more rare causes such as medication side effects, granulomatous diseases (such as sarcoidosis), and familial hypocalciuric hypercalcaemia must be considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient most likely has hypercalcaemia due to \u003Cstrong\u003Eparaneoplastic syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E. The hypercalcaemia is most likely a result of his underlying squamous cell carcinoma malignancy. Hypercalcaemia secondary to lung malignancy may arise from bony metastases or less commonly, tumour secretion of a parathyroid hormone-related protein (most commonly seen in squamous cell carcinoma), calcitriol or other cytokines, including osteoclast activating factors. Confusion is a late manifestation. Other paraneoplastic syndromes are more typically associated with small cell lung cancers and include SIADH, immune-mediated neurologic syndromes (eg, Lambert-Eaton myasthenic syndrome), hypertrophic pulmonary osteoarthropathy (HPO \u2013 which is defined by the presence of clubbing and periosteal proliferation of the tubular bones which manifests as a symmetrical painful arthropathy), dermatomyositis and polymyositis, and Cushing\u0027s syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHypercalcaemia is known to impair action potential generation in cells. This leads to a reduction in neuromuscular excitability that can present in a variety of ways, including decreased gut motility (leading to constipation and abdominal pain) and fatigue and cognitive impairment. Hypercalcaemia can also affect the expression aquaporin channels in collecting ducts, resulting in decreased water resorption (thus polyuria).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMedication side effect\u003C/strong\u003E is not the most appropriate response. Medication side effects could certainly lead to these symptoms, however, due to the variety of symptoms caused and the only known medications being chemotherapy-related supportive care agents, it is not the most likely cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrinary tract infection (UTI)\u003C/strong\u003E is not the most appropriate response. Abdominal pain can be consistent with a UTI, however urinary frequency would be more expected than polyuria. We would also expect to find dysuria, and likely flank pain and high fevers if we believe a UTI (or pyelonephritis) is causing his confusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBrain metastases\u003C/strong\u003E is not the most appropriate response. Whilst metastases to the brain could be responsible for these symptoms, it is not the most likely situation considering his recent diagnosis of squamous cell lung cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetes insipidus\u003C/strong\u003E is not the most appropriate response. Whilst diabetes insipidus could be a cause of polyuria, it does not account for his other symptoms. In fact, hypercalcaemia is a known cause of acquired nephrogenic diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A memory aid for the symptoms of hypercalcaemia is \u0022renal stones, painful bones, abdominal groans, and psychiatric moans\u0022"],"references":["Pelosof LC, Gerber DE. Paraneoplastic Syndromes: An Approach to Diagnosis and Treatment. Mayo Clin Proc 2010; 85:838-54."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37278"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"265"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37278","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37278"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-30T19:14:15+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-30T19:14:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"265"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51975"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici